Parliament has not ratified the amendment for the release of Tymoshenko
The Ukrainian parliament rejected, as part of an amendment to the criminal law, the draft annulment of the paragraph relating to the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the head of the opposition.
In the second reading, MEPs rejected the proposed amendment aimed at reducing the sentences for economic crimes, which could have opened the doors of freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for having entered into an a priori disadvantageous agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not final and the court is expected to rule on the convict's appeal in December.
Tymosenko called the ruling a political revenge of the regime and provoked a process of suspicions of partiality of the court also in the west.
The proposed annulment of paragraph 365 of the Criminal Law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 MPs.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve it.
