The diet of an obese child: do not take breakfast and take charcuterie for dinner
More than one-third of children aged 9 to 13 have overweight problems, 9% of schoolchildren are above average and 5% are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families that have an unhealthy lifestyle.
This again shows how important is the environment in which the human being evolves and the patterns that surround him.
On the tables of obese children, for example, charcuterie is found 50% more often than in families of children with normal weight.
19% of obese people had fries at dinner, according to the survey conducted with an awareness campaign "Obesity is not a coincidence"
In families of the big ones, sport is also not a habit, which is now the case for most schoolchildren today - only 15% answered that at least once a week parents found time for active movement.
A survey of 900 children
The survey took place during the last school year and involved 900 pupils from primary schools in the Czech Republic.
This was the second edition of "Obesity is not a coincidence", an action supported by the General Health Insurance and the company Unilever.
Since the beginning, more than 12,000 students from sixth to third grade have signed up for this project.
One of the determining factors that cause a dramatic increase in the number of overweight or even obese children is the lack of proper nutrition and not enough exercise.
“Only half of the children surveyed reported eating 5 times a day, for example, breakfast – in case of lunch – tasting – dinner, which is one of the basic principles of a good diet,” says one of the results of the survey.
Without breakfast and charcuterie at dinner
Specialists draw attention to the fact that to have a healthy development requires some basic details such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of student families eat at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats their breakfast alone.
And the worst that has been noted is that a tenth of the population does not eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast, however, is the basis of a good daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that in families of obese children, unhealthy fries are more often consumed.
Almost every student - not to mention the weight - drinks sugary drinks every day (70%).
More than 40% of the children surveyed regularly do sports, but for parents it is half, only 15%.
Prepare your diet
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own diets based on possibilities offered according to their own taste and personal opinion.
"The preferences of Czech children from 12 to 15 years old are far from ideal, in terms of a healthy diet."
Among their favorite dishes there are a lot of cakes, meats and sweets.
"The most alarming is a particular preference for sugary lemonades," the results of the survey said.
For lunch it is the pasta that took the first place right in front of the white meat.
The children did not want starches at all and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Heading to Health
The survey also showed that children are ready to change their habits from the moment they receive the ad hoc information.
“During a review of a group of survey participants who had completed the questionnaire after the awareness session ‘Obesity is not a coincidence’, a determined willingness to move towards a healthy diet was based on the results of the survey.
The most striking was, for example, with regard to sugary lemonades as children began to give preference to drinking water.
Children most often checked on the questionnaire white meat and fish as the main dish and would reduce sweet dishes and the "knedliky" (Czech specialty of bread flour or potato rolls).
