This annoys the most at the end of the game when you drive on a long bridge in the opposite direction.
The opponent must pass in front of you at all costs.
When it passes in front of you it hides the view of other vehicles in the opposite direction and you collide a lot of times.
One can understand that the purpose of this game is to do something captivating and full of adredaline, but it is clear that you get bored quickly.
And it's a shame because through a simple driving model the game is interesting and places with so much action that you don't have time to follow everything that happens.
And it does not matter if it is because of the concept of 50 unique routes, that the order of the races is such that there is no chance of getting bored or anything else.
The original idea is the change of car during races.
You need to pay attention to the petrol pumps on the routes as you can change the car there however most of the time the one you have is enough for you.
The cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are ideal for cities, large American cylinders for straight highways and super sports cars with exotic twists on very technical drives, for example on lace roads in the mountains.
And the mode of challenges, which are races in particular places you know about adventure, goes very well with the main diet of history.
You receive not only medals but also experience points that add to your profile that is common to challenges and adventure.
When you have reached the highest level of driver, different objects begin to unlock:
It connects online with the Autolog feature, which among other things compares your results with those of other players and provides you with other features in the community.
One of the most difficult blows to understand is the situation of the last race of the adventure.
You arrive with your car in the subway tunnel (it looks like) where you drive in the dark on the tracks (it looks like).
Your speed indicator shows you between 150 and 200 km/h (a priori) and behind you comes a subway that sends the car directly to the scrapyard.
At the editorial office we had a discussion for a few days about whether someone really thought when creating this game or if the authors really take us for fools.
The technical part of the game is not extra, but the visual part is generally nice and in some cases really great.
What is bothering is that in more extreme situations, the imagery does not hold the level and in some cases tragically.
This is especially true for accidents with a large number of participants when fluid imaging is no longer useful.
The sound is good and the track is a choice.
In order to please as many and especially the younger audience a new soundtrack was created in the style of "I mix everything", but one can expect that no one will buy the game for music.
Need for Speed: The Run is so confusing.
If the game didn't have these stupid mistakes we could say without fear that this is the best production of NFS in recent years.
