History of a brand:
IBM innovator begins the second century of its existence
If someone were to look for the word that expresses IBM's strategy as closely as possible, the closest would be "the long term".
For a wide audience IBM is the symbol of the technological revolution, is a firm felt as very current and yet since its creation it has been a hundred years.
The basis for this long-term strategy was laid by the firm's first chief executive, visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He left this slogan that a large number of global problems can be solved unless people are willing to think.
Its slogan "THINK!" became the imprint around which the life of a future giant will develop (and also the title of the internal magazine that IBM began to edit in 1935).
It was the basis of the company culture carefully crafted by Watson.
For us, IBM means long-term thinking of continuous movements towards the future.
IBM has survived a hundred years thanks to the fact that it has always remained true to its core values and yet has not been afraid to change all the others around it.
This enabled us during our first century to transform technology, business and society.
We hope that in the second century we will achieve even more," said the current director of the firm Samuel J. Palmisano.
A well-prepared system
Watson, in the 1930s, took care of his employees like Bata in the Czech Republic – IBM people were the only ones among the first U.S. employees to have paid vacations, an employer-paid insurance plus an elegant employee uniform and a well-developed reward system for inventors and commuters.
Similarly, IBM has a well-developed customer relationship system.
The company was at first brilliant at discovering talent- as one of the first firms to have abolished any form of discrimination and could thus have a choice.
The current plan is completely in the spirit of the anti-discrimination strategy since it will be a woman—Virginia Rometty—who should replace Palmisano at the head of IBM.
