IBM History: From slices of cheese to flights into the cosmos.
IBM (International Business Machines) was born in New York City a hundred years ago; it initially had the complicated name of Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM in 1924 - initially it was a brand used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America.
The basis of the future IBM was the merger of four firms whose history is related to the year 80 of the nineteenth century.
They possessed technologies such as the old "pointers", the pendulums that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 presided over the Supervisory Board of the company.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm, Thomas J. Watson, to help him lead the company.
The leader then overshadowed the founder of the firm - it is on the ideas of Watson that so far rest the identity and culture of the society.
Watson ran the firm in Kusqu in 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began with the production of all possible machines for business and commerce - from cheese and meat slicers to cash registers.
In the first four years of Watson's leadership, sales increased to $9 million and the firm began expanding in all parts of the world.
Watson was so irreplaceable for the firm that after 40 years of management, his son took the chair of director, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM's people and computers helped NASA guide flights into the cosmos - on Mercury, Saturn and in 1969, the flight on the Moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers, the IBM System/360.
The classic PC that determined the computer standard of the time with the IBM 5150 name came on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later IBM sold its computer factory to the Chinese company Lenovo, but bought the company from Consulting Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to deal with consulting and services with high added value.
The strategy that has been successful at IBM over the past three years - is the Smarter Planet concept "a smarter planet".
Its goal is the intelligent use of technology in areas not yet exploited, such as transport and urban management.
As far as the field of commerce is concerned, IBM recently developed a "Smarter Commerce" platform that helps merchants to manage the entire business cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in our area.
It established its branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932, then the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM RT, there is also the strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central for Central and Eastern Europe is based in Prague and there is also the world-class research and development team that deals with speech recognition.
