How Travel Prices Have Changed Since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered travel especially to the countries of the socialist bloc, because travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists travelled for holidays in East Germany, the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A big exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when it was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime began to have an inclination to the west and trips to Yugoslavia were very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
If the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West however it was necessary to queue all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good acquaintance" within the travel agency.
And even after that it was not yet won.
The currency agreement that was the prerequisite for traveling west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency, however, was not exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the agreement of currencies (Western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were therefore many country houses and cottages that the Czechs bought and this habit lasts until now.
The travel of the Czechs has experienced a great revolution since 1989.
Although until 1989 vacations in East Germany and Bulgaria were at their peak, Czechs spent 4 million holiday days abroad last year in countries around the world.
The great paradox of which we are not aware today is that the most popular country is Croatia, where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s in the western neighbouring countries caused a huge wave of short-term visits especially in Austria to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not for a long time travel by air to the west that everyone wanted to see for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, travel organizations made the Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay for the hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a trip from the Czech Republic was at that time to take with you your own canned food, sausage, etc... to save.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech crown which finally allowed our tourists after decades of being able to freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living as well as the average wage increased which caused another important moment around 1997.
As a result of increasing demand for travel, travel agencies have begun to prepare tours with air charter services since 1997, which through contracts have greatly reduced costs compared to before.
In the late 1990s the Czechs had visa-free connections with virtually most developed countries around the world except the US which later facilitated our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter to an exotic country, Thailand, was prepared from the Czech Republic.
Since this year, as every year, direct air charters take Czech tourists to distant hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolutionary development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the EU removed visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to completely fall into the group of developed countries.
In 2008 also the Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50, 3%) and for the first time again in history spent more than 15,000 crowns per person for holidays abroad including the accompanying charges.
