An architectural history with highs, lows and a Happy End: the Austrian pavilion for the World Exhibitions in Brussels in 1958 won prizes, was a museum in Vienna, remained empty and then fell into ruin.
Now it is reopened and takes place as an exhibition house.
If one is enthusiastic about a modern post-war architecture, for its clear shapes, its glass hangars, its bright and bold looks and its new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the pavilion of the Austrian architect Karl Schwanzer is for a good example in a universal exhibition in Brussels.
