He made the architects so famous, that he also built the Pavilion for the next Austrian Universal Exhibition.
With its legendary BMW four-cylinder house and adjacent bowl-shaped construction in Munich, it finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion project as a temporary construction had been exhibited after the universal exhibition in the Swiss Garden at Vienna's South Station, was transformed, and in 1962 a 20th century museum opened -
But the building was neither physically nor technically suitable for a museum - no walls to hang the works of art, so not a good environment.
However, it was so long used, until contemporary art received a new building in Vienna.
Since 2001, the building has been empty and has increasingly collapsed.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has transformed the Pavilion, it is now called the "House of the 21st century" and will be used in the future as a museum for contemporary art.
Tuesday evening the Belvéd<0xC3><0xA8>re museum opened, to which the house belongs, the first exhibition - a stroke of luck in every way.
The new beginning was completed by Agn<0xC3><0xA8>s Husslein-Arco, who became the new director in 2007 of the Austrian gallery Belvedere.
Husslein-Arco, promoted an art historian to a considerable career among others in her youth as an artistic skater, later at Sotheby's, at the Guggenheim Museum and as the founding director of the Museum of Modern Art in Salzburg, she has particularly accomplished the work of transformation among political men and public protection.
With the exception of contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba whose foundation bears the same name have been exhibited there, a café and a bookstore are located there, and an office must be built there.
Strict supervision, small budget
For the realization Krischanitz was therefore the ideal interpreter.
Not only because he had sensitively transformed and expanded the secession of Joseph Olbracht and he had won the competition, but because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and that for him the pavilion was "an extremely important place" where he had seen "practically every weekend" the exhibitions.
He knew the original project, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost in generosity and lightness as a result of his move to Vienna and through its change of use.
In the current transformations, there were major problems: the building was "an energy gap," says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facades were changed, insulating glass reinforced with fiberglass was laid and the roof replaced by a special safety glass.
The beams of the thermal bridges were reinforced or replaced, and the asbestos-filled coatings were rehabilitated.
Two basements have made room for the new operation, a sealed light panel between the house and the road ensures lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - it's almost a new construction, but still the light Schwanzer Pavilion.
