Peter Englund's new book, "The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War," begins with a long list of characters that will take you to heart.
A tip to get started: Carefully tear this page and make it your bookmark.
In this romantic story by Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a beacon during those few moments when, like one of his men or women, you will be troubled and desperate in the mist of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
He wrote here an unusual book which he accurately described as "a work of anti-history."
It contains a few well-known names, important treaties or famous battles; there are hardly any ambassadors or discussions about strategies and materials.
It's not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as a "book describing what it might look like" that contains "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods."
"Beauty and Grief" summarizes the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women, from both sides of the war, from young schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, to doctors, ambulance workers and salesmen.
Some of them will become heroes.
Some of the prisoners of war will lose limbs, go crazy, or lose their lives.
Their lives here waver like the candles of a church: while some are extinguished, new ones are rekindled.
Peter Englund’s book deviates from traditional history books.
It denies the idea that the First World War is only summed up by the terrible trench war on the Western front.
"Beauty and Grief" skillfully describes other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers present in this book are under hives; one spends Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; tsetse flies are an intractable problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
The war invades the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like a hurricane Katrina that smells of corditis.
When gunshots sound in the distance, and you're a mother at home, do you stay or do you run away?
Who will come anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, not even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, “the lack of facts has been compounded by assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors.”
"Beauty and Grief" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young sailor of the German High Seas Fleet.
Their stories are mainly drawn from memoirs, letters and other documents already published.
