7 Lessons from Steve Jobs’ Lost Interview at the Movies This Week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford - distinguished by the technical genius and inventor of modern computing.
But what Apple fans may find even more revealing in a recent Steve Jobs interview that will air this week in the first part of a film on major markets, is how creative this spirit had understood the processes and workflows of the products.
He was no doubt a creator and a dreamer. He identified himself as a hippie but was also very meticulous and organized, as well as an organigram enhancer - a man who believed that many business leaders suffered from an "illness leaving them to think that a great idea makes a lot of work...
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the television series "Triumph of the Nerds", which traces the birth of the computer, and he sat for more than an hour with Steve Jobs for a long and rare conversation.
At that time, it was about 10 years ago that Steve Jobs had had to leave Apple. He was already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, aimed at a popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of the interview with Cringely is used in Nerds, he states that the major copies have disappeared in transport.
It was only after Steve Jobs’ death that a full video was found in the director’s garage.
This video, slightly revamped, is the basis of the 68-minute film titled Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which will air in theaters on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Steve Jobs here seems surprisingly enthusiastic about exposing technology philosophies and his business strategies.
And incredibly attentive.
On four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs weighs his thoughts clearly, in order to provide a precise answer.
We also discover moments when Steve Jobs’ perfectionism resurfaces, when he seems eager to hear Cringely’s questions, giving him elbow blows to speed him up and move on to more important questions or topics.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod or the iPhone, we find a strangely precocious aspect on Lost Interview. Steve Jobs evaluates what he considers good or bad in other companies and shares his own vision of the future of computing.
It’s one thing to read the posthumous assessments of Steve Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about the man we see here, the anxious dreamer on the eve of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
He explains them and then implements them immediately.
Here’s a quick summary of seven notable Lost Interview sequences:
On how he learned to run a business:
“For all these years, I’ve always asked, ‘Why are you doing things?’ and the answers are constantly the same: ‘Oh, just because you have to do them.’”
No one knows why, no one thinks deeply about things in a company.
That's what I found out.
Steve Jobs continues by giving details of his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
Perplexed as to how the costs were recorded - one often starts with a "standard cost" assessed at a glance, then adjusted with a "variation" - he developed an automated factory that ensured the accurate calculation of commercial costs.
On the opportunity to play a tour of the Pope:
Steve Jobs tells the anecdote of the "Blue Box" he created with Steve Wozniak - a device that used to hack phone networks and make long-distance calls for free.
The device has been the subject of many writings beforehand, but Steve Jobs’ euphoria here in his description of the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a public telephone, making a call and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while bypassing as many satellites as possible.
“We wrapped the ball of different things half a dozen times and you were yelling at the public phone and it happened to you a minute later at the public phone next door,” Jobs laughed.
“We were young and through this Blue Box, we learned that we could create something ourselves that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
We didn't know much about each other, but we did invent a little thing that could control big things. It was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would ever have existed without it.
Steve Jobs continues by narrating a wonderful turn that he and Wozniak have made: he phoned the Vatican with the Blue Box in the middle of the night pretending to be Henry Kissinger and asked to speak to the Pope.
While several members of the Catholic hierarchy are summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two accomplices leave insanely laughing just before the Pope himself is awakened.
On his love of technology (and Bill Hewlett’s approach):
At the age of 12, on the hunt for spare parts to make a frequency meter, he searches for Bill Hewlett's number in the directory and gives him a phone call.
Shortly after their 20-minute conversation, Steve Jobs gets a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It had a remarkable impact on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my definition of a company and the way employees are treated."
Steve Jobs later became one of HP’s employees to visit the company’s research labs, located in Palo Alto, where he discovered the “first ever designed desktop computer.”
It was as big as a suitcase, had a small cathode tube. I fell in love with it.
The teenager I was back at HP and started writing programs for this machine.
On the Improvisation of Innovation:
At several times in the interview, Steve Jobs talks about inventing new products at a glance.
At the beginning of his career, as he settles down to sell a few printed circuit boards, a client asks him to assemble a complete computer.
Working at only 30 credit days, he had to take care of the assembly as well as the delivery of the finished devices.
Later, at Apple, he remembers the difficulties encountered in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember a lot of arguments... I was yelled at and pretended that it would take me five years [to make a mouse that would cost $300]. I had enough, I went out and I went to see a designer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could make for $15 and that turned out to be incredibly reliable.
On the big companies that are blowing away:
Long before he revived Apple, Steve Jobs had anticipated how many industry leaders would go wrong and lose control of their market share.
“Let’s say you work at IBM or Xerox, you make a better copier or a better printer, and then?”
You have the monopoly of the market, so the company does not meet more success.
Sales and marketing can make it evolve, so [these are these types of people] who end up leading companies and product-specialized personnel are set aside from decision-making.
The product engineering that led to this monopoly position is completely rotten by people who can’t imagine designing a good product versus a bad product – the required manual work.
This is what happened at Xerox.
Xerox could have owned the entire IT industry.
It could have made ten times its current size. Xerox would have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They snatched defeat from victory.
On innovation as an artistic form:
“A huge amount of manual work separates a great idea from an exceptional product... as you develop that idea, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about its subtleties.
There are compromises to be made... Some things you can’t do, electrons can, glass, robots, factories too.
You have to keep thousands of things in mind (these concepts) by assembling them together.
Finally, decisions are made by personal taste. It is about trying to expose yourself to the best products that men have created, and trying to bring these things to the product that you create.
Picasso once said that good artists copy and great artists steal.
We are always ashamed of stealing great ideas.
That's partly what makes Macintosh exceptional: the people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who simply turned out to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn’t for computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another field.
