How to spot a lie
A look at recent headlines indicates how ubiquitous deception and lies are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accusing the other of lying.
Penn State officials have been charged with perjury for allegedly covering up reports that a retired football coach sexually assaulted boys.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught by an open microphone telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
The lie has destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York Congressman and Internet celebrity Anthony Weiner, has posed as an idiot by quickly issuing denials contradicted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of violating campaign funding related to the coverage of an extramarital affair.
And then, none of those who have lived history will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton unleashed by lying during his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The cheating stories at school and university tests are legion.
There have been cases where teachers gave test responses to students in order to get a good look at their performance assessments.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How many deceptions do we encounter?
On a given day, studies show that you can hear 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are pious lies.
Another study showed that foreigners lie to each other three times in the first 10 minutes of their encounter.
Detecting or spotting lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a game of society similar to, say, charades, where the goal is to exclaim: "I have had you", the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades in prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research in such projects, in particular in psychology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lies have been demystified.
The liars look you in the eye.
They don’t sting, blush, or stir all the time.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to expose.
A qualified lie detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, facial micro-expressions, question formation, and response time.
I have spent several years examining scientific findings in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge about deception, and it is clear that deception detection is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful for navigating our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, negotiating, or managing.
Good liars are skilled at reading others well, making them comfortable, managing their own emotions, and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more lies "centered on themselves" while women tell more lies "centered on others" - usually to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie less often to their partners than unmarried people tend to be (but have to tell lies than unmarried people do).
We also know that if you are perceived as an unbeliever, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How can you tell if someone is lying?
First of all, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
This is what is called "setting the benchmark data".
This helps to provide a point of reference for measuring subsequent changes.
Observe the posture of your subject, laughter, vocal quality.
You need to know if someone is normally waving their feet all the time so as not to throw unfair accusations when you see them waving their feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for signs of misleading verbal and non-verbal behaviors.
Consider these clues as red flags, not evidence of deception.
Deceptive people can immobilize the top of the body when they try to remember their story, they can point their feet at the door, lean toward an exit, change posture significantly, or present a post-interview relief – an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change of posture when all the difficult issues have passed.
Questioners often falsely indicate that the interview is over just to try to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Also, pay attention to the vocabulary of your subject.
The famous Scott Peterson slipped away using the past while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Deceiving individuals can also use distant language: "I have not had sexual relations with this woman...Mrs. Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "wooden tongue" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to be honest... if I remember well... to my knowledge."
This makes the response perceptive rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for the detection of lies, but the development of skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone’s chances of avoiding victimization by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
