Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years and this translates into better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Delaying change, he argued, would be to postpone the benefits of digitization that involves a decision of public interest that has not only a technical dimension, "because this also includes economic, social, political and national security issues."
These issues, he stressed, "require the operation of an entire system established, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the state, includes a group of attributions that the Constitution grants to the faculty of the State Executive".
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition and they have done so through the Executive, despite the fact that they have the highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, in issuing the contested decree, has in some form invaded the sphere of competence of the Congress, because it ensures in the administrative sphere the observance of the laws issued by the Legislative, he assures.
