The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday.
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put the country on the verge of economic disaster.
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet with the President of Italy on Wednesday to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and endangered the entire Eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet Wednesday with the president, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that he can form the government.
He is expected to present a majority cabinet composed of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he would present to the president the outcome of his talks with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," he told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles had been overcome.
The "framework is now well laid out," he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than usual, while Italy is battling a political and financial crisis that has pushed the costs of its debt to levels impossible to sustain.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain confidence in Italy that had been affected.
By underscoring the pressure on Monti to hurry, market volatility put the yield on Italian BTP bonds at 10 years above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to be saved.
Emma Marcegaglia, the leader of the Italian employer Confindustria, told the media after her meeting with Monti: "We said we would greatly support this government."
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to emerge from this emergency situation.
Monti’s chances of success were greatly boosted by the support of Silvio Berlusconi’s PDL party, which the crisis forced to resign last Saturday.
"We believe that the efforts of Professor Monti will have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party, told reporters.
The support of PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because so far many of its members have opposed the majority technocratic government that Monti forms.
Parliamentary support
Monti’s new government needs strong parliamentary support to implement what are likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockade or delay in its efforts could provoke a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure by noting that a Monti bankruptcy would be a disaster.
On Monday, Monti began consultations with political parties, trade unions and employers' groups and youth and women's organizations.
He will end his tour of meetings Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who authorized an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi was going to resign, the costs of Italy’s debt have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty about the new prime minister’s success.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of 1.9 trillion euros, would be too much for the current financial defenses of the Eurozone.
Monti said his government should continue until the upcoming elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement the reforms before the elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but major parties insist that it should only be formed by specialists, an indication of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources have reported that mutual mistrust and disagreements between the parties complicate trying to include political figures.
