Quinteto included the country in its turn to celebrate two decades of trajectory
"Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In the exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to offer one of its best concerts next Sunday at the National Stadium.
They have waited more than 20 years, but the group assures that for them it will also be a dream come true to occur in this country.
This is what bassist and founding member Jeff Ament assured, speaking exclusively with Viva, from Brazil, last week.
The group is in the South American wing of its two-decade celebration tour and on Sunday 20 will make its only stopover in Central America.
On that day they will perform at the National Stadium, starting at 7:30 p.m., next to the Los Angeles group The X and the nationals of Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcript of which can be found in La Naci<0xC3><0xB3>n on the Internet.
For Costa Rican fans, the fact that Pearl Jam will take place in Costa Rica is a dream come true. Are you aware of what your fans are living?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is our second time in South and Central America and so far it has been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once for the holidays; it's such a beautiful country and I think we can spend a few days there.
We are excited to bring our music there.
I ask you, because there is a kind of devotion to the band, the fans live with intensity the previous days.
What is your message to your most fervent followers?
Thank you for staying with us for all these years.
It took 21 years for us to get to Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that so much time had to pass until this concert.
Some people already say that his concert is the biggest show of the year.
Does this add a bit of pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve offered over the past 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We have offered two gigantic shows in Sao Paolo and we hope it has put us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to producing it.
We love this country, we love surfing and the jungle; for both things, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
We have a lot of surfing friends and I have a very good friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves are amazing there.
My friends were always going to surf in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, next to Mexico, are great places to surf; this is how we learned, through people who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, you have offered huge shows, with a lot of songs.
What did you plan for your presentation in Costa Rica?
As we have never produced there, we have no restrictions as to what we can do.
We will try to do the best show possible, with a wide variety of songs; we will try to perform two songs from each album and offer our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What is this all about?
I think that’s partly because we have nine records and we can perform more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, that’s why it’s very difficult to choose which songs to perform every night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven’t performed in a very long time, it helps us stay focused and surprises us because it reminds us of the reasons why we loved those songs and that we may have forgotten.
This makes the show more interesting for us and therefore I think it also becomes more interesting for people.
With this tour, you celebrate 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve accomplished?
Yeah, absolutely.
First of all, I don’t think any of us had imagined we were going to be a big rock band, and the fact that we’ve been doing it for over 20 years makes it sound like a dream.
We continue to tell our blessings and being able to continue making music together thrills us a lot.
We love each other and we love making music.
We are lucky to go to places in the world that we have always wanted to go to.
Things couldn't get any better for us.
What does it mean for you to have been a fundamental element in the creation of the grunge?
It has always been an honour for us to be part of this group of large groups.
We are very friends with people from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and is uncommon.
From time to time, a group emerges from a city, but it is much more strange when five or ten groups leave the same city at the same time.
We are proud and it is an honour for us to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we went to a festival with Alice in Chains and we went to Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we’re lucky to still be friends with all of them and it’s an honor for us to be part of that Seattle sound that came out.
It's also very strange that a group like yours stays together and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, and only that is much longer than many bands normally last.
Firstly, I believe we are all lucky to be still alive and, secondly, we all care about others.
We are all close friends and thanks to this there are musical boulevards that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We have confidence in each other with each other’s music and it couldn’t get any better.
Your relationship with the word celebrity has not been easy; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do whatever you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we grew up, it was easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure that we don't spend too much time on tour because it's easy to fall into this game of large crowds and people who love your music.
If we don’t forget that people are there for music, it helps us not to forget that we have to respect the music and what brought it, without thinking about the fact that we are famous and a rock star, which doesn’t really interest any of us.
How do you remember your other project, Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote some good songs and at the beginning it was great.
We’ve been a band for almost three years and we didn’t release a record until Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There was a lot of frustration for the fact that it lasted so little and the most important is the fact that we are still very friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who started out in the group with us and when I listen to a song or I see a photo I think of the amazing person that Andy has been with football and how he was always making me laugh from it.
He was a surprising human being and we miss him.
The national group Las Robertas will open the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder and for that you chose her for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos with different proposals and this was the band we liked the most, so we’re looking forward to seeing what Las Robertas can offer live and it must be very distracting.
Why do you always change the lyrics of Yello Ledbetter live?
This is a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don’t know.
He is the one who sings it and I believe he does it with the first words he imagines.
As a bass player, what are his influences?
There are so many...
Among the first I remember are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many influences, I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I love.
How did Pearl Jam succeed in keeping the grunge relevant despite the fact that it is no longer in fashion?
I think we all feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I just mentioned, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all those that came up at the same time and, if that's relevant now, I think it's wonderful because it's music that's worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are now making the best music ever.
At first, his music had a darker content and now it has become more positive.
What is the purpose of this change?
That's interesting, because I think there are songs in the new album that seem lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe, that qualify as very obscure songs, even if they may sound a little positive.
With both of them, when Ed played them for me, I cried when I listened to them and these are deeply obscure songs.
I think that if you grow up and there’s trauma in your life and you lose a parent or friend, these things start to influence your art and your music and these songs probably represent that to me.
I also think that we can be happy and even like that we can make dark music.
