Fujimori hospitalized again for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized Tuesday in a public hospital to be assessed for the loss of muscle strength he has in his feet, his family doctor said.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights violations committed during his government (1990-2000), suffers from various conditions, including a tongue cancer for which he has been operated on four times and which is under control.
Congressman Alejandro Aguinaga, his personal doctor, told Channel N television that Fujimori will be evaluated for three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the cause of pain and loss of strength in his lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori would be a candidate to get the benefit of the remission of the sentence for humanitarian reasons, probably he said that he does not want it because he feels innocent.
He has been operated on four times for tongue cancer, he has a weight loss of 18 kilos, and other pathologies, such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst of the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and problems with circulation in the feet, the doctor listed.
Fujimori has been incarcerated since September 2007 in the National Directorate of Special Operations of the Police.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people because of an army annihilation squadron that operated clandestinely during the first years of his government.
