In the mid-1980s, at the height of the already extinct Metropolitan Corporation of Barcelona (CMB), this Administration printed promotional posters of Collserola.
The brochure defined the mountain as the great park of the metropolitan Barcelona.
In addition, it also contained a comparison, in figures, with New York’s Central Park.
With the death of the CMB in 1987, the park became again, in the imagination of many people, the upper limit of Barcelona, the Catalan capital being the only one that does not orient itself on the north-south axis, if not high (mountain) - low (sea).
The qualification of Collserola as a natural park is to the advantage of this idea.
The reference was no longer Central Park but Yellowstone, with wild boars in the role of the Yogi Bear.
This was the situation until, in September, the town hall convened a mega-competition composed of 16 contests for all doors to Collserola.
A door brings back the idea of a park, no doubt.
That's it, or someone wants to put doors in the field.
The question arises by itself: Collserola: park or mountain?
The competition, both in terms of its organization and in terms of reflection on the city, is a topic of conversation for all architects in Barcelona.
It’s almost a recurring theme that two members of this ancient caste of elects talk about when they recognize themselves in an elevator.
And this is precisely one of the few opinions that three architects from Barcelona, university professors, have come up with.
Miguel Rold<0xC3><0xA1>n, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: the contest is opportune.
For Rold<0xC3><0xA1>n, after addressing the coastal front "it is necessary" to debate "the mountain front" because the speech of Ildefons Cerda, that of the green house blocks was not carried out at the end.
"It is necessary to start from the base that the largest park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things, for its great accessibility.
Collserola is more complex," the architect for whom the title of "doors of Collserola" contains a "lexical trap": one should not think of them "as access to a park, but the demarcation of certain areas in which to act".
Modol, like Rold<0xC3><0xA1>n and Bayona with experience in the urban world, calls the proposal an "intellectual challenge" with "some dangers".
Dangers that derive from the "uncertainty of the projection of public space" after the experience lived in the 80s and that had in the area of the Forum "his swan song".
The first fear is the very demarcation of the borders on which one can build.
"Limiting something means already establishing the next step," that is, overcoming it.
