Secretary Dionisio Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come gives details of the air crash in which the Secretary of the Government, Francisco Blake and seven other people lost their lives
The Secretariat of Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results of the accident in which Secretary of Government Francisco Blake Mora and seven others lost their lives indicate that the helicopter struck directly at the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before the aircraft took off, the pilot found that the climatic conditions were adequate to fly.
"Elements that appear to indicate that the unit had various contact with the ground, the blades had contact with the trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage."
He also informed that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it met the requirements for transporting staff.
In addition, he said that investigations done in the impact zone do not report the appearance of parts on the ground.
"In research, it has been reported that there are no parts or components of the aircraft in another location, the impact has occurred in a structural way.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 passengers and met the requirements to carry them.
The ground had a slope of seven to 30 degrees of inclination.
For the time being, the secretary has ensured that a priority is to have the results as soon as possible; but the investigation can last a few months, it can even last a year.
In turn, Gilberto L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Meyer, Director General of Airports and Auxiliary Services, assured that at the time of the impact, the Presidential General Staff helicopter was operating at cruising speed and this happened on a movable ascending ground.
"This information supports the hypothesis of normal cruiser operation at the time of impact," he said.
During the press conference, the TBS holder, Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come, listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual Vol:
According to aeronautical regulations, the flight was carried out according to the rules of visual flight, which implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions: -
Reports in the IACM mentioned adequate conditions for take-off, and as the aircraft advanced to the border area between DF and the State of Mexico there were low-level cloud layers.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the cloudy conditions the crew searched for a lower height zone and more visibility towards the Cuernavaca valley.
Location of the impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last recording of the aircraft on the radar coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration of the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft remnants in a reduced area:
The information available so far suggests that the impact occurred on a straight and lateral trajectory.
The model of dispersion of the remains of the aircraft makes it possible to assume that the helicopter collided with the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
No traces of fire or explosion have been detected:
In the place of the disaster there is always no trace in the remains of the aircraft of a type of explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that the aircraft had had multiple contact with the ground.
During the field work, parts of the aircraft were found at a height of 9,200 feet above average sea level, the ground had a slope that went from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which he possibly disjointed himself along his journey.
The information provides elements that appear to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts with the ground.
After careful research in a wider area than the encircled area around the accident, no scattered parts of the aircraft were found, which supports the presumption that the impact took place under structural integrity conditions.
MSS Announces Protocol to Find the Obesity Gene
Social Insurance leads an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in the case of children and young people; this is supported by specialists of the IPN
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the obesity gene in children and adolescents, called the 'Obesity Genetics of Children and Adolescents' protocol that will have markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, Miguel Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, head of the Medical Investigation Unit in Biochemistry at the 20th Century National Medical Center Specialties Hospital, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Advanced Research and Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The investigation invites to participate the population with or without the right, to present themselves to the participating sports units of the IMSS in Valle de México, where the evidence to minors is carried out every Saturday from 8:00 am.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that from October 8, the activity takes place in the Nezahualc<0xC3><0xB3>yolt Sports Unit (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Independencia Sports Unit (south of Distrito Federal) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of Distrito Federal).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in children and young Mexicans to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
As World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on November 14, he mentioned that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and under the supervision of their parents, for the application of specific questionnaires related to food.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and family history of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that on Saturdays anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure, glucose, triglyceride, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetics (people associated with childhood obesity are sought to be identified) will be applied to all participants.
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez reported that this investigation is the result of health professionals' concern about the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
"The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in just six years there was a 77 per cent increase in obesity in boys and 47 per cent in girls; there was also a dramatic increase in overweight," said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from others by its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans have 65 percent Indo-American, 30 percent European and five percent African heritage and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy you consume (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the integral evaluation of the children, which allows to detect if they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
He even said that the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicate the likelihood of suffering from metabolic and even pre-diabetes alterations.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, the doctors hand it in writing to the parents, who are explained each of the measures and changes in the lifestyle they need to make to prevent diseases.
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentaryness, which is the lack of daily physical activity, sitting most of the day in front of the TV and using means of transportation instead of walking on short distances.
Another cause is high calorie intake, i.e. the highest consumption of sugary beverages, carbohydrates (tamales - cornmeal paste wrapped in corn leaves -, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and ashes in genetics.
UNAM’s asphalt would avoid cassis
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, develops polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mixture with better yield, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs that the pavement were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200 thousand broken pieces each rainy season in the México Valley Metropolitan Area, warns Rafael Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who assured that if the process of building and maintenance of the pavement was even completed, it would be possible for the pavement to be damaged.
During his conference A Technological Opinion on Crustaceans, organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with a higher mechanical resistance than those of asphalt, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve yields, and therefore, the formation of cassis.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltens, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthens, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, of almost 180 degrees, it behaves as a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it presents an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle.
This means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day depending on the environmental conditions and temperature, warns the specialist in chemical engineering.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de México were mostly covered by a flexible pavement, consisting of six layers of material, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Between the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and later compacted.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it by generating forces, it allows the forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, they would have spread better, according to the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt layer, he says, a last layer called the bearing layer is put, made of fine stone, that is, sand which is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide traction in the street.
As the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the stresses, the bearing layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be cared for.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, because these significantly affect the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil gets wet, the water spreads inside the layer it is difficult for it to come out, which softens all the layers of the pavement and therefore causes debris.
In the process of forming a cassis, he says, the first one that spoils is the rolling film and only subsequently the asphalt layer is affected, but the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that must be treated at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of cassis and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be related to the load of vehicles and ensure its satisfaction, to avoid frequent formation of cassis.
Rafael Herrera has warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and make it possible to repair debris easily and without having to use high temperatures.
