Hundreds of demonstrators were huddling in front of Zuccotti Square, where they wanted access thanks to a court order that allowed the "indignant" to camp again in this place, while the other side of the movement responded to the evacuation by occupying a park further north of the city, where there were new stops.
“Our idea is that if the court does not allow us to camp again in the square, we will settle in another place and we will continue the legal struggle to return to Zuccotti, and through sit-ins and peaceful demonstrations,” said Mark Bray, a spokesman for the Occupy Wall Street movement.
Bray detailed that the 'indignant' response to the evacuation of their camp personally dictated by New York Mayor Michael Bloomberg has reached the courts, where Judge Lucy Billings issued an order banning forced evacuation of the place and allowing protesters to remain in the camp.
In addition, the 'indignants' occupied a new park located at the confluence of Canal Street and Sixth Avenue, very close to the entrance to the Holland Tunnel, which unites New York and New Jersey, owned by Trinity Church Parish.
At least for an hour they managed to occupy the place, but after the police moved there and arrested some demonstrators, although Bray was unable to confirm the concrete figure, assuring Efe that he saw some journalists who had also been handed handcuffed.
The organization says there were hundreds of people who had settled in this place, where a delegation of religious leaders moved in support of the members of the movement and tried to intervene in their favor in front of the police.
Meanwhile, the Zuccotti Square - which is a privately owned enclosure - remains closed pending the celebration of a court hearing scheduled for Tuesday during which the legality of this morning's evacuation must be analysed.
Some of the protesters who had been displaced so far were carrying and distributing copies of the court order at that time and they were even delivering it to the officers who were monitoring the square, which caused “some small clashes,” said Bray, who denounced the fact that some officials had hit the protesters.
The court order prohibits the authorities from evacuating members of Occupy Wall Street or applying “laws issued after the beginning of the occupation or prohibiting protesters from re-accessing the park with tents or other properties they previously used.”
Mayor Bloomberg told the press that, because of the court order, the city had suspended the reopening of the space to the public and protesters, whom he warned, however, that local laws do not allow them to settle with tents and sleeping bags.
The municipal councillor personally defended the evacuation carried out at dawn in the Zuccotti square, an operation during which 200 people were arrested and which was decided because the demonstrators "violated the law".
Bloomberg explained that he had ordered the evacuation because it became "a place where people did not come to protest, but to violate the laws and in some cases to hurt other people", because "some stores had received threats" and residents were afraid "for their quality of life".
"This morning's evacuation at dawn has been repugnant and shows that Bloomberg is more interested in defending the financial interests of American workers than those of American workers," the spokesman added, accusing the mayor of "not respecting freedom of expression."
“Occupy Wall Street” officials also said they do not plan to hold “great actions” for Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and trade unions to commemorate the two months of protests, which began on Sept. 17.
