Japan resurfaced after the earthquake
GDP rises 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the spiral of decline from the beginning of March
Since March, Japan’s economy has been paralyzed, recovering even after the devastating earthquake that has become a nuclear crisis, Japan’s worst disaster since World War II.
Initial estimates by the Government of Tokyo estimated the material losses at $300,000 million, a blow which, despite the difficult global context, appears to have subsided.
After three consecutive quarters of declines, gross domestic product data between July and September served to permanently turn the page: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% at an annualized rate.
The one recorded in the second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - assumes, in addition, the largest rate of increase since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly due to the resumption of acquisitions of equipment to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to a decrease of 0.9% in capital expenditures from January to March, the first decline after six months of uninterrupted growth.
However, the real stimulus of the Japanese economy is not based solely on the Keynesian impulse that invites to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - the infrastructure, use the shortcomings to grow from scratch.
Japan woke up mainly thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japan's GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, driven by increased spending on vehicles, travel and entertainment activities.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo returned to the domestic market when the yen - the Japanese currency - became one of the "refuge values" chosen by investors fleeing the eurozone debt crisis and the turmoil forecasts of the United States, a privilege that weighs like a slab in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger currency, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic floating line is determined by the health of large technology groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, accounted for their poor results between July and September in the yen.
While markets continue to be based in the EU’s peripheral countries, the Yoshihiko Noda government does not lower its guard.
“We need to monitor the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of Thailand’s floods and the rapid appreciation of the yen,” said Secretary of State for Economic Policy Motohisa Furukawa.
And indeed, the prospects are not encouraging at all.
The Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) said that the majority of member countries showed clearer signs of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates the turning points of the world economy has highlighted that the main powers are being held back.
Because it fell four decimal places to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 in August.
The Eurozone has even been below the average, which is in the 100 level, n dropping eight decimal points to 99.13 points.
