The feeling that the "consensus" of the new Greek transitional government is rather imposed by the demands of Brussels than by a real conviction of the political forces begins to be confirmed by the facts.
While the new prime minister, Lukas Papadimos, yesterday reported that there is no alternative to structural reforms and that the period of one hundred days established in his appointment may be short to apply them, the leader of the conservative New Democracy party, Antonis Samaras, assured that he was not going to support any new austerity measures.
