A package of 24 programmes to stimulate employment, the reform of the Staff Disciplinary Code and new measures against tax evasion will be the first initiatives.
However, Samaras' message does not cast doubt on his position: "We are committed to helping the Transitional Government, but we are committed to nothing more."
The conservative leader has gone one step further in his pulse than the EU and IMF, the agencies that must unlock the 8,000 million that Athens urgently needs, and has said clearly that he will not approve any letter of commitment to make adjustments.
But the European Commission, still irritated by the impact of the Papandreou referendum, reiterated yesterday that its demand is firm: it will not unlock aid if the new government and the leaders of the main Greek parties do not sign "a written commitment without ambiguity as soon as possible".
Economic Affairs spokesman Amadeu Altafaj said the troika's inspectors would return to Athens "very soon" to discuss with the new government "the elements necessary to pay for the sixth instalment" of 8,000 million, even if there is no definitive date either.
