Energy policy:
The facts must prevail over the dogmas.
If it is a subject that cannot be dealt with from short-term considerations or under the influence of emotion, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is healthy that an election meeting should be an opportunity to reflect on such issues and on the role of nuclear power.
The debate will only be fruitful if it explores all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
While we are 7 billion human beings on the planet, demographic change will lead to a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, unless it deprives a huge part of the world’s population of a vital element.
At the same time, it will be necessary to alleviate the scarcity of fossil resources in order to continue to produce electricity permanently, not to mention the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate disruption, a topic that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not alter any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains isolated in its decision to give up nuclear power.
This is not the case for Belgium, which submits its own to the need to be able to find a replacement source capable of replacing itself, nor for Switzerland, which just wants to build only the latest generation power plants.
Conversely, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name just a few, continue their projects with determination.
The United States decided after Fukushima to add a unit to its park by resuming the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, focused on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, reality contradicts the discourse.
The choice of Berlin will result in an increase in the price of electricity, an energy dependence exacerbated by the increased use of imported gas, especially from Russia, a spike in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of gas and coal power plants.
Within a few months, all these nasty effects are already being felt.
The case of Denmark is to be meditated on.
Europe's champion of wind, from which it draws 30% of its electricity, it is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to the intermittent wind; under which, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
Conversely, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than that of French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy is a key factor of competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining the industrial tool on the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear power would result in a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would make illusory the beautiful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power.
A price that a large majority of French people refuse to pay, especially since they do not show principle opposition to this energy, the polls show.
Recall that our country's energy policy has helped to build an industrial sector of 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 induced jobs.
Highly exporting, it brings a galaxy of specialized SMEs into international markets and makes them very job-creating non-delocalizable.
If France decided to leave nuclear power, it would sacrifice many of these SMEs by reducing the 6 billion euros of annual French exports of nuclear equipment and services as a pity.
What electrician would order an EPR designed to run for sixty years while its manufacturer’s decline would be programmed?
To solve the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no source of miracle electricity production, nor is there any diabolical one.
Areva's development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear, maintaining the highest level of security is an absolute imperative.
We have in France a Security Authority that exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing plants as well as over the Flamanville site.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, are inhabited by the same obsession with safety.
In a half-century, the nuclear industry has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, intervened under normal operating conditions; it remained without human or environmental consequences.
In Chernobyl, the design of the reactor and unforgivable human faults caused the drama.
In Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident is the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that have caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it did for the previous two.
As a result of this approach and of cooperation between the safety authorities, the operators and the French and German manufacturers, the EPR presents a design that enables it to withstand such phenomena.
While it is considered by all electricians eager to build a power plant, stopping its construction in Flamanville would be a magnificent gift offered to competitors from Areva and EDF by leaving them free to take the lead in the unavoidable development of nuclear.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy package for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let the emotions, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate such a decisive debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
