As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in a recent paper synthesizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among experts on the impact of migration on the economy.
Restricting immigration anemics growth and harms employment.
Fears about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they are likely to take the place of national workers, especially the low-skilled, putting downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, mostly in occupations in sectors with a lack of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national employees, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors in which training does not follow the job offer.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon will struggle to work in a country with a shortage of anesthesiologists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants make immigrant arrivals have a positive effect on national wages and employment.
Giovanni Peri calculated that an increase of 1% in migration flows leads to an increase of between 0.6 and 0.9% in long-term real wages.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (a high proportion of immigrants naturalized among the US Nobel prizes; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, averaging 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany, an immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (receipts minus expenses) of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>150,000 to public budgets on average over his entire life.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of his term, to go look for the missing growth points "with his teeth".
The teeth in question, used to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, it remains to think about European democracy
Democracy is a precious asset; it is also a fragile asset.
The European continent should be able to remember him who, for having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, experienced throughout the twentieth century the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that it would suffice, for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, to exercise the vote, and to exercise it in the most direct manner possible.
It is known, since Napoleon the Little, that this was an ease of thought.
Universal suffrage, in order to be the necessary condition of democracy, is not the sufficient condition and can even become an "instrument of oppression", as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, the Enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis of Europe that we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is also and above all a crisis of politics and democracy.
In this respect, the palinody of the true and false Greek referendum has had the value of a double revealer: that of the need for a powerful return of politics, but also that of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be thought to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle have now shifted, and for many of them, Republican soldiers are no longer pulling in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain by demanding a succession of national referendums, organised as necessary and in a dispersed order.
A white-sing to the absolute European monarch or a leap together in the void of the nationalist retreat: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want cuts, but an exercise, common, full-fledged, serene and continuous, of choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, in Italy, in Spain, in Portugal - there is nowhere else to stop the enumeration - because there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe that is bowing to the dictates of markets and rating agencies, suffering from its impotence and lack of solidarity.
The whole of Europe is humiliated on the international stage.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe - but it is the whole of Europe that is slowly losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The urgency is to give back to popular sovereignty the leadership of the European project.
Because it is together that Europeans will be able to reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from markets and prepare for the future by investing.
The exit from the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, except, of course, to lead us to disaster.
After long fighting this proposal of the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for the European economic government.
Well, maybe.
But to think it without stronger political and democratic integration, and lived as such by citizens, would be a new madness and a new impasse.
We need to take a new stage in European construction.
To make the Republic in France, it was necessary to “make” Republicans.
The Revolution in the interests could not suffice.
This lesson remains valid.
We need to build a more economically integrated Europe.
This can only be done by building a more politically democratic Europe, a true European people's sovereignty.
To make Europe, let's make Europeans.
