The Nord Stream, the new gateway of Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Western Europe directly to Russia via the Baltic Sea, has entered service.
It has to supply gas for the equivalent of 30 million homes.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with brilliance.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part on the Baltic coast last Tuesday, between orchestra and buffet, at the inauguration of Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline that connects Russia directly, under the sea, to Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte turned together the steering wheel of the valve commanding the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new gas pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive every year in Western Europe through a first 1,224 km tube connecting the St. Petersburg region to the Mecklenburg-Vorpommern Land.
A second tube must be completed by the end of 2012, providing a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, the equivalent of all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third one on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction site looks like a victory.
The project had been strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord Stream will deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries lose some power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies there.
But it is at the cost of a weakening of Europe's energy, since the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has triumphed over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the wealthy Western countries, which are heavily gas-consuming, and whose deposits are declining.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically," Fillon confirmed when inaugurating this gas pipeline, demonstrating how large gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles displayed by the leaders of Gazprom, present in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater tube is made of concrete-clad steel to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at 200 m on average.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
“A hundred or so had to be abducted or destroyed, as a precaution,” said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
There was also a need to increase measures to protect the fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, as heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, that nothing interrupts over its entire length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project officials renounced it while the Swedes were reluctant to see a Russian state-owned company settle permanently off their coasts.
“In the event of a breakdown, we stop the passage of gas in less than a minute,” says Jens Müller.
In the event of leakage, the gas contained in the gas pipeline thus escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who planned the welds to experience a leak every 100,000 years.
The state of the gas pipeline is monitored by an underwater robot, carried by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an apparatus circulating inside the gas pipeline.
In the form of a cigar, it is introduced into the tube, wide by a meter in diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
On arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 meters second, it delivers accurate information about possible deformations of the metal.
The gas pipeline was designed to run for fifty years without having to undergo any repairs.
The circulation of the gas is simply ensured by the pressure.
It is 200 bars at the start, and 100 at the finish.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), Dutch Gasunie and French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies set up a joint venture, Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to this company, for twenty years renewable, the entire gas transport capacity.
“Gasprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported,” says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the gas pipeline was provided to 30% by shareholders and to 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works is expected to reach <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.4 billion for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to pay their costs, since only Gazprom takes the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specifics of the gas that arrives, before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour it passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
