Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th week for the employment of disabled people opens today.
Despite a voluntary public policy set up in 2005, the unemployment rate for people with disabilities is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared to 9% for the entire population.
Discouraged?
"No," said <0xC3><0x89>ric Blanchet, general manager of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of disabled people.
"The progress made in the last 15 years is considerable. "
“At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher.”
"However, there is still a lot to be done."
It must be said that for the disabled, there are still many obstacles to accessing employment.
They are quite old: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the degree and of the 2.3 million higher education students, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very prevalent: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
In short, so many criteria that make it particularly difficult to return to work, and that "are the nucleus of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
This is for objective brakes.
What remains is the unsaid, the mentalities that are evolving, of course, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité indicated that the managers interviewed had "a low level of knowledge of disability", with "overrepresentation of wheelchair users, mental or intellectual disabilities".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the 6% employment target for disabled workers, set in a 1987 law.
The last known figures, which date back to 2008, report a ratio of 2.6%.
“We are now around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: the number of "taxed" establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also translates into real awareness, especially in large groups.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
